flowent

Class Flowent

  • java.lang.Object
    • flowent.Flowent
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Cloneable

    public class Flowent
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Cloneable
    Flowent is a fluent interface API written for the Java Programming Language.

    Flowent is a project by CodeDojo, developed by many different CodeDojo developers. From a user's perspective, it looks nice and simple, while the API does all of the work for you.

    Starting version 1.0.1, this class is now cloneable via Object.clone(). Also starting version 1.0.1 is a logging feature. If you have overriden onError() in one of your custom methods, for loops, while loops, or anything else, but you run into an error and are not sure what is goig wrong, you can call the constructor Flowent(true) and a debugging log file will be created at ~/.Flowent/log/flowent-log-<DATE>-t-<TIME>-<ID>.log

    Version:
    1.0.2
    See Also:
    Cloneable

      • runMethod

        public Flowent runMethod(FlowentFunction ff)
        Runs the execute method in the FlowentFunction passed in.

        If the method execution has any uncaught exceptions, the onError method will be called. No arguments may be passed in.

        If an error occurs, and the logging option is set to true, the standard error will be added to the log file.

        Parameters:
        ff - The FlowentFunction method to be run.
        Returns:
        This Flowent object for method chaining purposes.
        See Also:
        FlowentFunction, FlowentFunction.execute(Flowent), FlowentFunction.onError(Flowent, Exception, Protocol)

      • runForLoop

        public Flowent runForLoop(FlowentForLoop loop,
                          int iterations)
        This method takes a FlowentForLoop object and executes it's iterate method over iterations times. The first iteration is passed in to iterate as iteration 0. If an error occurs during the iterate method, onError picks up.

        If the logging option for this object is set to true, and an error is thrown, it is logged in the output file.

        Parameters:
        loop - The loop to run in a for loop
        iterations - The number of iterations to run through
        Returns:
        This Flowent object for method chaining purposes
        Since:
        1.0.1
        See Also:
        FlowentForLoop.iterate(Flowent, int), FlowentForLoop.onError(Flowent, Exception, Protocol), FlowentForLoop, FlowentWhileLoop

      • runWhileLoop

        public Flowent runWhileLoop(FlowentWhileLoop loop)
        This method runs a given FlowentWhileLoop's iterate method until it returns true.

        There are two cases in which during the loop will stop automatically, before the JVM crashes due to stack overflow.

        The first way it will stop is if the loop is executing to fast. It can sustain 60 FPS at a maximum recommendation. If it runs faster than the JVM can handle for 100 consecutive iterations, it is stopped. Do not confuse this with stopping the program.

        The second way is if the iterate method runs into at least one error for 50 consecutive iterations. After that, the while loop will be broken.

        Parameters:
        loop - The while loop to be run
        Returns:
        This Flowent object for method chaining purposes
        Since:
        1.0.1
        See Also:
        FlowentWhileLoop.iterate(Flowent, int), FlowentWhileLoop.onError(Flowent, Exception, Protocol), FlowentWhileLoop, FlowentForLoop
